 22:27:02','','It\'s dreamy weather we\'re on\r\nYou waved your crooked wand\r\nAlong an icy pond with a frozen moon\r\nA murder of silhouette crows I saw\r\nAnd the tears on my face\r\nAnd the skates on the pond\r\nThey spell Alice\r\n \r\nI disappear in your name\r\nBut you must wait for me\r\nSomewhere across the sea\r\nThere\'s a wreck of a ship\r\nYour hair is like meadow grass on the tide\r\nAnd the raindrops on my window\r\nAnd the ice in my drink\r\nBaby all I can think of is Alice\r\n\r\nArithmetic arithmetock\r\nTurn the hands back on the clock\r\nHow does the ocean rock the boat?\r\nHow did the razor find my throat?\r\nThe only strings that hold me here\r\nAre tangled up around the pier\r\n\r\nAnd so a secret kiss\r\nBrings madness with the bliss\r\nAnd I will think of this\r\nWhen I\'m dead in my grave\r\nSet me adrift and I\'m lost over there\r\nAnd I must be insane\r\nTo go skating on your name\r\nAnd by tracing it twice\r\nI fell through the ice\r\nOf Alice\r\n\r\nAnd so a secret kiss\r\nBrings madness with the bliss\r\nAnd I will think of this\r\nWhen I\'m dead in my grave\r\nSet me adrift and I\'m lost over there\r\nAnd I must be insane\r\nTo go skating on your name\r\nAnd by tracing it twice\r\nI fell through the ice\r\nOf Alice\r\nThere\'s only Alice.','','','tom-waits-alice','Tom Waits, \"Alice\"'),(375,'nehar','2009-01-15 09:30:17','emacs shortcuts','M=alt(meta) key(or escape)\r\n\r\nShell:\r\nM-! command: run \"command\" in a shell\r\nM-| command: run \"command\" in a shell; use region contents as input.\r\nM-x shell:   run interactive shell in window\r\nM-x term:    run interactive shell in window; with full terminal emulation\r\nM-x eshell:  run emacs shell\r\n\r\nMisc modes:\r\nM-x global-font-lock: turn on syntax highlighting.\r\nM-x line-number-mode: toggle line numbers in mode line\r\nM-x column-number-mode: toggle column numbers in mode line\r\nM-x display-time: display time+system load\r\nC-u 66 C-x f: set line length to 66.\r\n\r\nMovement:\r\nM-v scroll forward\r\n\r\nwindows:\r\n         C-x 0  (delete current)\r\n         C-x 1  (delete all others)\r\n         C-x 2  (divide horizontally)\r\n         C-x o  (go to other)\r\n         M C-v  ( scroll other)\r\n         C-x 4 f(find file in other)\r\n\r\ncase conversion:\r\n        C-x C-l (convert select region to lower)\r\n        C-x C-u (convert select region to upper)\r\n        M-l     (convert word to lower and move forward)\r\n        M-u     (convert word to upper and move forward)\r\n        M-c     (capitalize word and move forward)\r\n\r\nsearch and replace:\r\n       M-x replace-string: replace string.\r\n       M-% : queried search and replace.\r\n           options  are:\r\n             Space: replace text and find next\r\n             del:   ingnore current and find next\r\n             .:     replace text and stop\r\n             !:     replace all\r\n             ^:     return to previously replaced text\r\n       C-x M- M-RET: repeat last queried search n replace.\r\n','some shortcuts etc i use frequently.','','emacs-cheatsheet','nehar'),(376,'nehar','2009-01-15 09:34:28','sed','replace first occurrence of foo on each line by bar:\r\nsed -e \'s/foo/bar/g\' myfile.txt\r\n\r\nreplace each occurrence of foo by bar:\r\nsed -e \'s/foo/bar/g\' myfile.txt\r\n\r\nreplace all occurrences of foo with bar but only on lines one through ten (inclusive):\r\nsed -e \'1,10s/foo/bar/g\' myfile2.txt\r\n\r\nadd \",important_datum\" to end of all lines.\r\nsed \'s/$/,important_datum/\' filename\r\n\r\nget the second last field out of a csv file with 6 fields.\r\nsed \'s/^[^,]*,[^,]*,[^,]*,[^,]*,\\([^,]*\\),[^,]*$/\\1/\'','some simple sed magic.','','sed-csv','nehar'),(377,'nehar','2009-01-16 09:12:54','rdesktop','get remote window in 100% of screen:\r\nrdesktop -K hostname.domain.net  -P -g 100% -a 24 -x l -B -u narora\r\n\r\nTo switch between full-screen and windowed mode: ctrl+alt+enter','','','rdesktop-commandline','nehar'),(379,'nehar','2009-01-16 09:17:10','*nix commands','ldd: show shared libraries requied by binary.\r\nulimit: (bash) set or display the os memory limits.\r\ndig -x 10.111.187.1 : get a dns lookup response on ip\r\niconv: convert encoding of file.\r\n\r\n\r\n','some unix/linux commands of use.','','some-unix-commands','nehar'),(381,'nehar','2009-01-16 09:20:04','vi cheatsheet',' ~ in command mode: change case of character under cursor.\r\n\r\n J in command mode: join current line with line below.\r\n\r\n :%s/search_string/rep_string/g  in command mode replaces\r\n all occurances of search_string by rep_string in the file.\r\n\r\n copy/paste in visual mode\r\n\r\n1. v: character based visual selection (visual mode)\r\n    V: line based visual selection\r\n    ^V: vertical block selection\r\n2.  use d/y to cut/copy and p to paste to replace selected text use c\r\n\r\n v[count]>      shift the highlighted lines [count] \'shiftwidth\' right\r\n v[count]<      shift the highlighted lines [count] \'shiftwidth\' left\r\n\r\n','vi shortcuts i keep needing.','','vi-cheatsheet','nehar'),(382,'nehar','2009-01-19 09:13:57','X server','showrgb:    view rgb color-name db (x)\r\nxmode:      Calculate X11 Modelines\r\nwmlist:       lists known windowmanagers\r\nfc-list:        list available fonts\r\nxlsfonts:     server font list displayer for X\r\nglxinfo:      display info about a GLX extension and OpenGL renderer\r\nxdpyinfo:   display information utility for X\r\nsax2 -p :    show detected graphics cards\r\nxfontsel:    point and click selection of X11 font names\r\nxset:         user preference utility for X\r\n\r\nxrdb -load ~/.Xdefaults: reload .Xdefaults\r\nXnest 3 -ac -name Fluxbox & fluxbox -display :3\r\n                run nested window manager (fluxbox in this case)\r\n','some useful X server related commands','','x-server-commands','nehar'),(383,'nehar','2009-01-19 09:18:51','windowmaker','wmsetbg [image]: set desktop background to image.','','','windomwmaker','nehar'),(384,'nehar','2009-01-20 11:04:30','Kill','If you\'ve got a runaway process that\'s respawning faster than you can kill it, then there\'s a couple of nifty Kill tricks:\r\n\r\n1. su to the user and run \"kill -9 -1\", this\'ll kill all of that users processes or more accurately kill all process that you can kill. and kids, don\'t try this as root :)\r\n2. Way cooler way -  \"kill -STOP -1\". This will stop all running processes that can be stopped. you can then kill whichever processes you want (there won\'t be anymore  respawning since all of that users processes are stopped), \r\nthen  \"kill -9\" the rouge processes. \r\n\"kill -CONT\" processes you still want running (kill -CONT -1 to restart all remaining processes.)','how to kill a runaway processes on unix linux.','','unix-kill-command','nehar'),(385,'nehar','2009-01-20 11:40:52','Bash For loop','for ((i=0;i<=42;i+=1)); do  echo $i; done\r\n\\----------\r\n\r\nfor i in {1..42}; do echo $i; done\r\n\\----------\r\n\r\nfor i in $(seq 42); do echo $i; done\r\n\\----------\r\n\r\nx=`ls`; for i in $x; do echo $i; done\r\n','some for loop examples in bash scripting.','','bash-for-loop','nehar'),(386,'nehar','2009-01-23 16:48:57','svn: undoing changes','sucky way:\r\nsvn copy -r [rev] http://server.com/project/trunk http://server/project.com/trunk -m \"reverting\"\r\n\r\nbasically overwrites the trunk with a previous version of the trunk. if someone made changes behind your back then they\'re effed.\r\n\r\n\r\nnice way: \r\nsvn merge -r COMMITTED:PREV http://server.com/project/trunk\r\n\r\nMerging backwards will get rid of everything committed between the two version. So, for instance, the above command gets rid of everything that was committed after PREV to COMMITTED(including COMMITED.)\r\n','subversion magic.','','svn-undoing-changes','nehar'),(387,'nehar','2009-01-23 17:08:01','svn: difference between two revisions','svn  diff  -r231429:HEAD  https://server.com/trunk/foo','some svn diff samples.','','svn-diff-between-two-revisions','nehar'),(388,'nehar','2009-01-23 17:12:11','svn: merging two separate branches','svn merge  https://server.com/trunk@255327 https://server.com/branch@255307','','','svn-merge-url-to-url','nehar'),(389,'nehar','2009-01-23 17:15:08','svn: revert all change in a directory','svn revert --recursive localdirname','revert all changes from local workspace.','','svn-revert','nehar'),(390,'nehar','2009-01-23 17:20:59','svn: Merging a branch back to trunk','branch-dir: Local working directory for branch.\r\ntrunk-dir: Local working directory for trunk.\r\nbranch-url: url of the branch in the svn repository.\r\nN: revision no. at which we branched off.\r\nM: revision no. of trunk head.\r\n \r\n1. cd to the branch local working directory branch-dir (or alternatively check out from repository.) \r\n2. svn log --verbose --stop-on-copy http://branch-url (run svn info to find out svn-branch if you need to) \r\n3. Note the revision number N shown in the earliest log entry (by date) from the output of svn log (from step 2 - this would be the entry right at the end of the log output).\r\n4. cd to local work directory of trunk (trunk-dir) and run svn update (or check out from repository - you don\'t need to run update in this case). \r\n5. Note the revision number M displayed in the \"At revision M\" (or \"Checked out revision M\" if you checked out from trunk instead of running svn update) line from the output of 4. \r\n6. run cd trunk-dir \r\n7. run svn merge --dry-run -rN:M http://branch-url \r\n8. if everything looks all right then run svn merge -rN:M http://branch-url This should apply the differences to the working copy (trunk-dir in this case.)  \r\nNOTE: If the merge does not seem right/yield expected results, or you see an error such as \"Revision x does not match revision y on some file/dir\", revert back the merged code by running svn -R revert, and run the merge again with the --ignore-ancestry option. svn merge --ignore-ancestry -rN:M http://branch-url\r\n 9. svn status to review local modifications - resolve any conflicts. \r\n10. svn commit -m \"message\"\r\n\r\nNote: Make sure that the message you add for the commit includes the range of the merge (e.g. \"merging rN:M to trunk\"). svn DOES NOT track merges in the log, so unless the message contains the revisions merged, that information will be lost.\r\n \r\nAlso, doing the same merge twice is an UNSAFE operation. so doing step 8 twice could leave your local working copy in a trashed state.',' ','','svn-merge-instructions','nehar'),(391,'nehar','2009-01-23 17:50:45','some useful sql queries','constraint query\r\n\r\nalter table DID_NUMBERS disable constraint FK_ACC_ACC_NUM;\r\n\r\nselect table_name,constraint_name from user_constraints where constraint_name like \'FK%\';\r\n\\-------------------\r\n\r\ncopying mySQL table across schemas:\r\n\r\nto copy contents of item_master from billing schema to FUNCTION_TEST schema -\r\nfirst:\r\n\r\nmysqldump -u billing -p -h 10.111.1.100 -B billing --tables ITEM_MASTER -t > item_master.sql\r\n\r\nthen:\r\n\r\n mysql -u function_test -p -D FUNCTION_TEST -h 10.111.1.100 < item_master.sql\r\n\\-------------------\r\n\r\ninvoice tax query:\r\n\r\nselect i.item_code,i.sub_total, t.tax_amount, t.tax_type,\r\n m.transaction_type_pct, m.service_code_pct\r\nfrom INVOICE_ITEM i, INVOICE_ITEM_TAX t, ITEM_MASTER m\r\nwhere i.invoice_number=<invoice number> and i.invoice_item_id = t.invoice_item_id and m.item_code = i.item_code\r\n\\-------------------\r\n\r\ntruncate table statement:\r\n\r\nTRUNCATE TABLE tablename','some mysql queries i need every once in a while.','','sql-queries','nehar'),(392,'nehar','2009-01-24 13:53:21','','Democracies die behind closed doors.','','','democracy','Judge Damon Keith, \"6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, Cincinnati\"'),(393,'nehar','2009-01-25 22:30:36','','Wipe your hand across your mouth, and laugh:\r\nThe worlds revolve like ancient women\r\nGathering fuel in vacant lots.','','','wipe-your-hand','T.S. Eliot, \"Preludes\"'),(394,'nehar','2009-01-25 23:10:20','','I am moved by fancies that are curled\r\nAround these images, and cling:\r\nThe notion of some infinitely gentle\r\nInfinitely suffering thing.','','','moved-by-fancies','T.S. Eliot, \"Preludes\"'),(404,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:18:35','','In the name of trust\r\nIn the name of familiar lies\r\nIn the name of love\r\nwhatever that signifies\r\n\r\nin memory of rust,\r\nin exchange for dust,\r\nfor a little bit more,\r\nmaybe a lot less,\r\neverythings fucked up\r\neverythings a test.\r\n\r\nin the name of trust\r\nwhat would you wanna be\r\nits fucking catharsis\r\nor maybe thats just me\r\n\r\nin memory of rust,\r\nthe bitter taste of dust,\r\ndoesn\'t really matter,\r\nmaybe i\'m blessed,\r\neverythings fuckin awesome,\r\ncan we give it a rest?','','','the-name-of-trust','nehar'),(405,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:20:07','','And i, \r\nwho felt myself promethus unchained in your shadow, \r\nmust shrink to my own form, \r\nknowing that gifts, forsaken or not, remain given.','','','promethus-unmade','nehar'),(406,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:20:46','','by your  very existence you stand  condemned of an  unpardonable act of defiance.\r\n','','','by-your-very-existence','nehar'),(407,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:23:56','','Don\'t even try to comprehend,\r\nlets all just keep trying to pretend,\r\nand when you think of her smiling at the break of day,\r\nremind yourself that it never pays\r\nto need what you need, and want what you want\r\nafter all, it\'s just another one of those days.\r\n\r\nAnd i know we must pay tomorrow,\r\nfor the sins of today\r\nBut baby i\'m too weary\r\nstill paying for yesterday.','','','dont-even-try-to-comprehend','nehar'),(408,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:25:31','','It\'s just a little dance of pain\r\nit\'s just a little sadness,\r\nIts just not worth your while\r\nto believe in all this madness.\r\nAnd when you see in the distance\r\nthose who called your name,\r\nRemember, whatever you might have thought\r\nIt\'s always just a game.\r\n\r\n17th nov 2005\r\n','','','sadness','nehar'),(409,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:26:10','','Darkness comes to ease\r\nwith silent comfort.\r\nFalling shadows bring succor,\r\nsoothing oblivion shrouding lost causes and foolish debts.\r\nTaking some weight of half forgotten pasts.\r\nWith a mortal shuffling gaze i seek some probabilistic explanation of you.\r\nAnd Death brings us all our own passing strangeness.\r\n','','','darkness-comes','nehar'),(410,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:26:34','','you are but a stain on the soul of a fractured reality.','','','reality','nehar'),(411,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:27:53','','as the world falls apart,\r\nwe sit and wait.\r\ni should have been the flaming heart of creation.\r\nyou should have been the burning sword of freedom.\r\nand yet - here we are.\r\nthere is no new story to tell.\r\nthere are no saviors of the sublime.\r\nthere should be.\r\n\r\n27th June 2008\r\n','','','stories','nehar'),(412,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:30:25','','in the time it takes to go back home\r\nin the time it takes to die\r\nin the time it takes to draw a breath\r\nin the time forgetting lies\r\nanother few drops of blood\r\nanother few miserable rhymes\r\nbaby, all it boils down to is,\r\njust a little bit more of my time.','','','little-bit-more-of-my-time','nehar'),(413,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:32:11','','I have spent too much blood on this,\r\nThis scent of a lingering pain\r\nthat so much catharsis hasn\'t washed away.\r\nVisions and love I could speak of,\r\nbut to what end?\r\n\r\nIf you could just see, for a moment, how I see\r\nI would show you a thing so tender and so true,\r\nThat you\'d know belief again, and pain.\r\n\r\nIn every moment that we rebuild our certainties with the breath we draw,\r\nI consecrate another brick to this.\r\n\r\nBut what could I build?\r\nto what purpose?\r\nHow could I keep the soft summer rain\r\nfrom washing away all that stands?\r\n\r\nAnd I am weary. too much blood.\r\nToo much that must be given again and again\r\nfor an edifice built on sand.\r\n\r\n17 July 2005\r\n','','','lingering','nehar'),(414,'nehar','2009-02-27 21:33:22','','We\'re all driven.\r\nAnd the devil dancing on the edge of perception drives you to your destiny,\r\nor your doom\r\nAnd would you dare think  you know which is which?\r\nWould you dare say \"I have seen and understood and I choose\"?\r\nWould you dare stand still and believe?\r\n\r\nAnd even when all you have left is the devil,\r\nthere will always be roses\r\na bit faded and forlorn, maybe,\r\nbut beautiful as you first thought them.\r\n\r\nAnd if I were to say \"Oh, but I have faith\"\r\nwould it matter?\r\nAnd if I were to say that I have seen and thought such beauty,\r\nand I have known such desire, and believed in such madness\r\nthat it can scarce be false,\r\nwould that be any use?\r\n\r\nI know enough not to be fooled,\r\nknow enough not to have false faith and false hope\r\nBut I can hear music that will not be denied\r\nand feel things deeper than I can understand.\r\nAnd what else can you do when you are lost,\r\nbut follow the music?\r\n\r\n15 July 2005, 1:53 am.','','','lost','nehar'),(416,'nehar','2009-03-22 16:24:17','some pieces i\'m playing','I recently decided to go through the standard studies of Sor, Carcassi, and Leo Brouwer. I\'ve been learning a mix of different pieces but it seemed a little haphazard. Hopefully this\'ll give my practicing a little more structure. \r\n\r\nI bought *25 melodic and progressive studies op 60 by Matteo Carcassi* (edited by Eric Dussault, isbn:2-89500-821-3  - this edition doesn\'t contain any left hand fingering), and *Twenty Studies for the Guitar by Fernando Sor* (segovia 2nd edition, isbn: 0-79350436-8) on my instructors recommendation, and will most likely get the brouwer studies once i\'ve made some progress.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the pieces i\'m playing these days - with youtube links of people playing em\'.\r\n\r\n- [etud no. 2, opus 60 - Carcassi](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2Lgg-JnTEds) - some random guy playing.\r\n- [etud no. 3 in A, opus 60 - Carcassi](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fnGoHClRN0U) - no idea who this dude is.\r\n- [canarios - Gasper Sanz](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iyhF9KEiDsc) (John Williams playing - wow, he looks such a nerd in this!)\r\n\r\nHere\'s stuff i\'d *like* to say i\'m playing these days:\r\n\r\n- estudio 1 - Sor, Twenty Studies for the Guitar\r\n- [asturias(leyanda) isaac albeniz](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oEfFbuT3I6A) (John Williams playing)','my repertoire','','repertoire','nehar'),(417,'nehar','2009-04-06 17:05:39','why?','apart from the need to add to the vast ocean of mediocrity that is the intrawebs, there\'s a couple of reasons why I wanted to set this blog up.\r\n\r\n1. easier for friends and family to know what I\'m upto  - hi mom, hi dad!\r\n2. needed a place to keep my notes, bookmarks etc. and what could be better than the intertubes!!\r\n3. I\'m sort of a geek and this is the kind of stuff geeks do - i\'m just conforming :)\r\n4. Wanted to learn Django. Haven\'t really had a chance to do much front end stuff (as you can probably tell from the site design.) I\'m hoping to put up a few useful django apps up here in the future, and who knows, someone else might find the code useful.\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you\'re looking to see how the code works, you can check it out from svn: <https://svn.nehar.webfactional.com/blog/trunk/>\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you\'re looking to see how I work, browse through the site. This is how I roll.','','','about','nehar'),(418,'nehar','2009-04-06 17:06:12','Who am i?','I\'m a 28 year old software developer living and working in New Jersey. My interests include computers and technology - obviously, I wouldn\'t set this site up otherwise - playing classical guitar, reading, and generally existing. I also enjoy art, but only as a spectator since I suck at it  - i couldn\'t draw a cat to save my life. I can do a mean fish though. Every once in a while, when the muse is upon me, I write.\r\n\r\nOn regular weekdays, I can be found slaving away at Vonage and even though it\'s not cool to like your employer, I kinda like working for Vonage - sad, but there you go.','','','about','nehar'),(423,'nehar','2009-04-24 18:51:24','enabling java remote debugging','add this to your JAVA_ARGS\r\n-Xdebug -Xrunjdwp:transport=dt_socket,server=y,suspend=n,address=1044\r\n\r\nyou can now connect to port 1044 with the remote debugger.','','','enabling-java-remote-debugging',''),(425,'nehar','2009-05-19 09:07:05','','We are stronger than our skin of flesh and metal, for we carry and share a spectrum of suns and lands that lends us legends as we craft our immortality and interweave our destinies of water and air, leaving shadows that gather color of their own. Until they outshine the substance that cast them.','','','we-are-stronger-than-our-skin','anonymous'),(426,'nehar','2009-06-25 22:57:16','','It\'s far under the old, old sun,\r\nthere is a heart to the heat.\r\nDust blooming like flowers of mist.\r\nThere is memory here,\r\nand a tightening of breath.\r\nAnd serrated edges that focus on the horizon...\r\n... or point at the past - \r\nit\'s always hard to tell.\r\nThe day seems shorter still. \r\nSomehow... Constricted at the pith.\r\nThere is truth to be found here - or so they say.\r\nMaybe. There is a rightness to the thought.\r\nAfter all, there is a feel of something...\r\nat the edges - always at the edges.  \r\nNever mind.  \r\nThis is what I choose to remain.\r\nThis and nothing more.\r\n\r\n2009-06-24, 11:42pm','','','far-under-the-old-old-sun','nehar'),(427,'nehar','2009-07-24 08:25:58','','Yet creeds mean very little, Coth answered the dark god, still speaking almost gently.  The optimist proclaims that we live in the best of all possible worlds; and the pessimist fears this is true.','','','yet-creeds-mean-very-little','James Cabell, \"The Silver Stallion\"'),(428,'nehar','2009-12-12 17:54:32','','And you write in blood,\r\nand you write in blood,\r\nant you write in blood,\r\nsongs that are long dead and gone.\r\n\r\nBy the edge of fear,\r\non the edge of fear,\r\nOn the edge of a rhyme long gone.\r\nOn the edge of a love long gone.\r\n\r\nWe were as gods,\r\nwe were as gods,\r\nwe were as gods \r\nwith the breath of our soul long gone.\r\nThe light of our soul long gone.\r\n\r\nIt\'s made of trust\r\nit\'s made of trust,\r\nit\'s made of trust -\r\nThis need for truth long gone.\r\nThis need to run long gone.\r\n\r\nAnd the brave will die,\r\nand the good will die,\r\nWith the gift of dust all gone.\r\nWhen all the dust is gone.\r\n\r\nThey say you believed,\r\nthey say you foresaw \r\nyou knew it would all be gone.\r\nBefore the foretelling was gone\r\nbefore the innocence was gone.\r\n\r\nIt\'s all the same\r\nIt\'s all the same\r\nyou can taste the truth long gone\r\nthe taint of dust long gone.\r\nThe time is long long gone.\r\n\r\nIt\'s all good, It\'s all fine\r\nwe fucked up the tune\r\nwe missed the beat\r\notherwise was a hell of a song.\r\n\r\n-2009-11-25, 2:06am','been listening to waay too much modest mouse.','','write-in-blood','nehar'),(429,'nehar','2010-02-11 18:04:50','using symmetric encryption with gpg','I like to keep important stuff on my machines encrypted with a pass phrase.\r\n\r\nencrypting:\r\n`gpg -c foo #(puts encrypted file into foo.gpg)\r\nsha512sum  foo.gpg >foo.gpg.sha512 #(generate fingerprint for foo.gpg into foo.gpg.sha512)`\r\n\r\ndecrypting:\r\n`sha512sum -c foo.gpg.sha512 #(check fingerprint; should get back \"foo.gpg: OK\" )\r\ngpg -d foo.gpg #(enter the same pass phrase used to encrypt)`\r\n\r\n','','','using-symmetric-encryption-gpg-i-keep-important-st','nehar'),(430,'nehar','2010-06-03 08:36:07','','If you want to build a ship, don\'t drum up the men to gather wood, divide the work and give orders. Instead, teach them to yearn for the vast and endless sea.','','','vast-and-endless-sea','Antoine de Saint Exupry'),(431,'nehar','2010-08-23 16:43:58','android debug app on device','Here\'s basic setup I needed to get my Samsung Galaxy S to show up under Ubuntu (Jaunty):\r\n\r\ncreate a new file (or a append to existing if you\'ve already got one) /etc/udev/rules.d/51-android.rules with following contents and read all permissions:\r\n\r\n\\#Samsung vendor Id is 04e8\r\nSUBSYSTEM==\"usb\", SYSFS{idVendor}==\"04e8\", SYMLINK+=\"android_adb\", MODE=\"0666\"\r\n\r\nrun:\r\nsudo service udev restart\r\n\r\nif you run adb devices now your device should show up.\r\n\r\ngot this information from:\r\n<http://eddieringle.com/debugging-your-android-application-on-the-g1-or-any-android-device-in-ubuntu-904/>\r\n\r\nand here:\r\n<http://groups.google.com/group/android-developers/browse_thread/thread/1c55ed426623e2b8>','','','android-debug-app-device','nehar'),(432,'nehar','2010-08-25 14:54:18','awk','get a count of  unique values in the first column of file (foo is the file name):\r\n\r\ncat foo  | awk -F \\\\, \'{print $1}\' | sort -u | wc  -l\r\n\r\nreplace the comma with whatever your field separator is. replace $1 with whatever column number you\'re looking for. Counts unique values - get rid of sort -u to get everything.','awk awk','','awk-column-capture','nehar'),(433,'nehar','2010-09-21 08:18:28','ubuntu  high disk io (ureadahead)','Ran into this a couple of times - started seeing constantly high activity on my laptop (apparently happens in earlier versions of Ubuntu too.)  log messages had a bunch of messsages like \"ureadahead-other main process (1111) terminated with status 2\"\r\n\r\nin my case was caused by me having hibernated my windows partition which Ubuntu kept trying to mount - so for me the fix was easy - restart and do a full windows shutdown. \r\n\r\nif you don\'t wanna reboot - http://www.mail-archive.com/ubuntu-bugs@lists.ubuntu.com/msg2014163.html ','','','ubuntu-high-disk-io-ureadahead','nehar'),(434,'nehar','2011-03-07 07:54:34','','The ones that win are the ones that ship.',' http://diveintohtml5.org/past.html','','ones-win-are-ones-ship','Mark Pilgrim'),(435,'nehar','2013-07-12 07:21:09','','For a few brief moments in time, we become the things that we do.','','','few-brief-moments-time-we-become-things-we-do','nehar'),(436,'nehar','2014-09-02 01:52:28','','I am the shell. I am the words.\r\nMemory before loss\r\nThought before the grave.\r\nWords are lost, language dies\r\nYet there must remain believers - bereft of faith if need be\r\nTo mark the passing of the divine.','','','i-am-shell-i-am-words-memory-loss-thought-grave-wo','nehar'),(437,'nehar','2014-09-20 22:47:51','','And how can man die better\r\nThan facing fearful odds,\r\nFor the ashes of his fathers,\r\nAnd the temples of his Gods.\"','','','and-how-can-man-die-better-facing-fearful-odds-ash','Thomas Babington Macaulay, Horatius/Lays of Ancient Rome'),(438,'nehar','2014-10-14 07:31:37','','In this mad spinning world \r\nYou - you are the immovable center \r\nAnchoring my reality\r\nWith your very being, shaping the fiber of mine. \r\nI know of the impermanence of life \r\nThe triviality of existence \r\nBut in theses few moments of peace \r\nI can feel the shape of eternities.','','','mad-spinning-world-you-you-are-immovable-center-an','nehar, 2012-10-08'),(439,'nehar','2015-06-13 15:43:44','','In this liquid world,\r\nIn this fluid, fluid, fluid world\r\nHow do I remember to run and breathe at the same time. \r\nRun, run, run while the minutes drain through\r\nMine and yours, darkness claims its piece of flesh. \r\nI raise my hand - and my armies rise\r\nI raise my hands - and the blood tide rises\r\nIn this crumbling place, in this tiny narrow place\r\nIn this mean small space. \r\n\r\nRemember this. \r\nI raise my hands \r\nRemember this\r\nI raise my head\r\nRemember this\r\nI raise my eyes\r\nRemember this\r\nlook up at the sky\r\nRemember this - before the breath slips away. \r\n\r\nThere were those of us who thought of this\r\nThere were those of us who remembered this\r\nIn this liquid world \r\nIn this fluid, fluid, fluid world\r\nBreathe and run, breathe and run, breathe and run\r\nHow do I remember to breathe and run at the same damn time\r\nOn this spinning, rocking world\r\nThe divine slips away as we run and breathe, \r\nrun and breathe, \r\nrun and breathe,\r\nrun and breathe, \r\none last damn time. \r\n\r\n\r\n','','','liquid-world-fluid-fluid-fluid-world-how-do-i-reme','nehar, 05/21/2015, 10:30 pm'),(440,'nehar','2016-01-24 22:13:41','','In some slow time,\r\nand another deeper space,\r\nI could be bigger than this...\r\nI would be - more unfathomable.\r\nA broader river winds through \r\nthe woods,\r\nand I would follow if I could \r\nThe brighter starlight that falls -\r\nif only I could see it as I should.\r\n\r\nWhile all the truth that I can muster waits\r\nexpectant... lingering, in the silence,\r\nthe slowed time passes...\r\n...and the  wider spaces shrink.','','','some-slow-time-and-another-deeper-space-i-could-be','nehar, 06/22/2015');
